Brand NIB Ruger SR1911 "Commander" .45ACP pistol.

title: For Sale:  250 rounds of 7.62x54r in a Maxim ammo can
postcontent:
For sale: 250 rounds of belted Bulgarian made (Circle 10) 7.62x54r in a Maxim gun ammo can. Please note that this ammo can be un-belted very easily for use in rifles.

The ammo was manufactured in the Bulgarian Circle 10 factory in 1971. It is lacquer sealed and silver tipped. It has been belted on a Soviet made 250 round non-disintegrating ammo belt.

The belt is 250 links long with feed tabs at both ends with the proof mark 17/53 stamped into them. It has never been used in an MG, and as such shows no wear or rust. 

The ammo can itself is a soviet made can designed to be used in conjunction with the M1910 Maxim machine gun, or the later SG-43 Goryunov. It has the late war style canvas carry handle, and is in pretty good shape despite its age. 

While the ammo has been belted, it can still be easily removed by simply pulling it out with your fingers if you intend to use it in rifles like 91/30s or PSLs. And if you intend to leave it belted, it will feed through a Maxim, SG-43, or PKM machine gun without any problems. The ammo can will also fit just fine in any mounts designed for those 3 weapons (If you're lucky enough to own one!)

Available for local pickup only, cash only. Upon purchase I will need to see your ID to affirm that you are over the age of 18 as well.

title: For Sale:  CZ 82 like new
postcontent:
CZ 82 1989 manufacture. This pistol looks and feels like new, does have the Century import mark on the slide otherwise impeccable.  Check out the barrel pic, no wear at all.
Comes with 2 mags, issue holster and cleaning rod.

Manufactured by the Czechoslovak firm Česká zbrojovka the vz. 82 replaced the 7.62x25mm Tokarev vz. 52 pistol in Czechoslovak military service in 1983. It is a compact, double-action, semi-automatic pistol with a conventional blowback action. This type of action allows the barrel to remain solidly fixed to the frame, resulting in improved accuracy over pistols with pivoting barrels (like the U.S. M1911 series). The low bore axis of the vz. 82 provides for less muzzle rise and quicker follow-up shots. For added convenience, both the frame-mounted thumb safety and the magazine release are ambidextrous. The vz. 82 was the first service pistol to feature both these features. The bore is chrome plated, which gives it three advantages: longer barrel life, resistance to rust from the use of corrosive ammunition, and ease of cleaning. Another feature of this pistol is the use of polygonal rifling in the barrel bore. This replaces the traditional lands and grooves rifling design with a rounded, smooth polygonal pattern which has a more "hills and valleys" appearance.
